The paper deals with the computation of the Longest Unbordered Factor Array of a word, which is a problem related to string algorithms and data structures. Therefore, cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) is the most likely category. The algorithm presented in the paper has a time complexity of O(n log n) with high probability, which suggests that it may involve probabilistic techniques and randomized algorithms, making cs.CC (Computational Complexity) another likely category. The use of logarithmic factors in the time complexity also suggests that the paper may involve information theory (cs.IT) or formal languages and automata theory (cs.FL). Finally, the paper may also be relevant to machine learning and pattern recognition (cs.LG) since these fields often involve the analysis of large datasets and the use of efficient algorithms for processing them.
